<h1>From William Ramsay</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dr Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Camp near Rays Town Augst 31st 1758.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Since my last nothing remarkable hath occurrd, only an express sent by Colo. Burd from the Mountains, is supposd to be gon to Fort Du Quesne. This may be of very ill consequence indeed. It seems this fellow was for sometime a Prisoner amongst them &amp; had the character of a great villain, yet was made one of the Pensylvania light horse, &amp; intrusted it seems with affairs of
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0431">[431]</span>
such moment; how imprudt this was, needs no comment. Another sent down to the Genl is thot, to be taken.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Amidst this gloom of ill fortune &amp; delays, we have the strongest asurances of Louisburg being ours, that our Fleet ravages the Coast of France &amp; that we may hope some important blow may be struck there, God grant this, for Im affraid, as I hinted before, Loyal Hannan will be our outmost effort this year. The Genl was to leave Shippensburg at yesterday, but I am affraid, he neither is, nor will be able to get here this season. I cannot divine why Men born down with age &amp; infirmities &amp; thereby renderd incapable of action, shoud be imployd in affairs of such momt &amp; in a Country that requires robustness to bear fatigue, &amp; resolution to excute with celerity this interprize; especialy as we have great reason to suppose, chief part of their force were imployd to Oppose Genl Abercrombie, &amp; how dear Genl Braddocks delays cost us.</p>
<p>I daily hope to be releasd from this place, my affairs realy call me home, tho: my stay will be short there, for I must soon set out for Williamsburg, where you may probably have some affairs to transact which the greatest care shall be taken of if intrusted to me.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Yesterday an old Indian named Cassatee, who was sent abt three Weeks ago from this place, has been at Loggs Town &amp; some other adjacent ones, &amp; has brot with him three Indians of the Six nations, but what they report has not transpird.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> I have nothing further to add, but a tender of any service in the power of Dr Sir Your very H. Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Wm Ramsay</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>In a draft of a letter to Forbes on 31 Aug. Bouquet wrote: Received the two Letters of the 26. and 28. and as I See no mention made of my letter of the 21st wth one of Major GRI am afraid it has been intercepted, as one of Capt [William] T[h]ompsons Light Horse [of the 1st battalion of the Pennsylvania Regiment] Named Th[os.] Glen deserted the 29th Inst wth all the Letters from Sir John [St. Clair] Col. [James] Burd and Major [James] Grant to me, which he carries to [the French]. . . . He is a Roman Catholic and has been a long time a Prisoner wth them (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald H. Kent et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Henry Bouquet&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Harrisburg, Pa., 1951-94. ]">Stevens, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bouquet Papers</span></span>, 2:44952). The brackets around os. and the French are Stevenss.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0328" class="document">John Carlyle wrote GW on 22 Aug</a>. that Ramsay was Much Wanted in Alexandria and Winchester, but in his letter of 12 Sept. Ramsay says nothing of leaving Raystown. Ramsay wrote <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0066" class="document">GW from Williamsburg on 17 October</a>.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0432">[432]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Col. James Burd wrote from his Camp at Quemahony early on the morning of 30 Aug.: Last night the Indian Gishaty [Kissity] arrived here with three more Indians with him one of which Named <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Adeneyachea</span> gave the Major &amp; self a draught of F: Du Quesne which he drew with my Pincel before us (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald H. Kent et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Henry Bouquet&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Harrisburg, Pa., 1951-94. ]">Stevens, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bouquet Papers</span></span>, 2:44849). In the draft of his letter to Forbes on 31 Aug. (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0350&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0001#GEWN-02-05-02-0350-fn-0001" class="document">note 1</a>), Bouquet wrote that Old Kissity returned last night from his Errand &amp;c. (ibid., 44952).</p>

</div>
